metadata.name: GEN XYZ Das Occult #4219
metadata.description:
A 10k Generative Profile Pic collection
GEN XYZ Das Occult - by culla - @tamccullough

move over cryptopunks
there is a new group on the scene

100% code - not an image composition

A bunch of common palettes
A selection of rare palettes
And a smaller set of ultra rare palettes
However, rarity will be based on what combinations the code produces

The majority of tokens will not have a special trait
However your token might have one or even multiple special traits
But, be aware that only the last special trait added will be listed in the features

Even then, look closely, because not all aspects of the canvas are included in the features. Collectors should still look closely and choose what they like when buying on secondary.

Which team are you on? X or O?

follow culla on twitter for updates. Or maybe __acolyte__

If the non reserved tokens mint out quickly, Access List mints will have 24 hours to mint reserves assigned to those wallets

Thank you for supporting an emerging artist in the generative art space

Access List reserves were given to holders of the following PFP collections created by culla
2x for each Basqunk held
1x for each Inkspunk, TwoFourQunk, V0iD, DeeManz, Punkasso and CR0$$KULL
You would have needed to transfer the above tokens to your mint wallet at the time of the snapshot

share your tokens on social media with #genxyznft
Made with love by culla using p5.js

metadata.name: Chromatic Waves #55
metadata.description:
Threads of color are weaved together, interacting and vibrating.

SVG generated with JavaScript.

The SVG can be saved by pressing "s" on the full-screen view.
A PNG version can be exported by pressing "e" on the full-screen view.

By default the dimensions of the export are 3200×2400.
These dimensions can be changed by adding, for example, ?w=3200&h=1800 to the full-screen page URL, where w is the desired width and h the desired height. Then press "e" to export at this size.

metadata.name: Sabler : Serengeti #86
metadata.description:
'Sabler : Serengeti' is a special edition reissue of the original Sabler generator in a vibrant 'Serengeti' palette which was omitted from the original collection. 

Towards the end of the production of the original Sabler collection, the creative decision was made to reduce the number of palettes from the thirteen that had been created to a smaller number, in order to improve the cohesiveness of the collection overall. While 'Serengeti' remained one of the stronger palettes, it was ultimately excluded in favour of the 'Annaliese' palette, in homage to an Anni Albers tapestry that originally inspired the 'Sabler' collection. 

Here, the 'Serengeti' palette is provided as a companion piece to the original Sabler collection to give collectors the opportunity to pair their output with their existing collection if they choose.

Below follows an edited description for the original 'Sabler' collection:

'Sabler', an anagram of 'Albers', is a generative homage to the work of the Bauhaus textile artist Anni Albers.

The aesthetic of this piece and its proportions are guided by the Golden Ratio (1.618 : 1) and as such, each part of the composition relates in some way to its larger self.

As lines playfully extend and overlap one another from various grid segments, patterns appear, 'ghost' shadings emerge and complexity is implied even with the use of very simple elements.

There are no rarities or special features, other than for you to enjoy the unique qualities of your piece!

You can save a high resolution 3000px x 3000px PNG of your edition by pressing the 'S' key.

metadata.name: Release #20
metadata.description:
[…]

More than anything she had wanted to show him where she had lived, where, at a specific time every year, endless fields sent a new cycle of pods on their way.

She preferred to experience these moments alone, imagining the spectacle was being performed just for her. The whole act carried a promise of new beginnings, of paths yet to be taken.

She wasn't really part of any of this, but she too had the coordinates to her own life programmed into her genes.

Any decision would be true now, any path free.

A chorus of explosions sounded as the field burst open.

[…]

–

You can append these parameters to the URL:

[scale=<number>] scale the renderer.
[long-side=<number>] define the number of pixels of the longest side.
[animation=false] skip animating the lines.
[mode=monotone] activate monotone mode.
[detail=<number 0–1>] coarser (0) or finer (1) lines, default: 0.5.

Press [control / command + s] or [tap and hold] to save the current frame.
	- in normal mode: PNG file.
	- in monotone mode: SVG file, suitable for plotting.

Note: The monotone SVG file has no defined dimensions. It is suitable for plotting at 30 × 30 cm. with a 0.25 mm. pen tip. When plotting in larger sizes, you can increase the [detail] parameter to keep contrast with the same pen.

metadata.name: Hope #458
metadata.description:
Ups, downs, and everything in between. This series is about prevailing hope in the journey of life.
Each brush stroke is meant to elicit perspective, connectivity, beauty, and hope.

Features:
F  -  Fullscreen
S  -  Save image
2/4/6/8/0  -  Change image resolution (press number key and then reload in live view, please wait a few seconds for higher resolutions to load)

Designed in p5js
Original artwork, 2022 by fauxjebus and Dave Siegel

“To live without hope is to cease to live.”
- Fyodor Dostoyevsky

Our skies in the next 30 years as temperatures are intensifying and we experience, in the present, unprecedent heat waves. 

Inspired in polaroid images. Each output represents an image, a collectible and a document of perpetual suns. 

Each image showcases a random date and time in the next 30 years.

Oftentimes we will see how the suns try to breach the borders of the polaroid. They seldom manage to completely invade the frame.

Press “s” to save a png image.
Press “h” to save a high resolution: 5500 x 3660 or 3660 x 5500 png frame.

metadata.name: Zaratan #153
metadata.description:
The Generative Token chooses between three primitives (cubes, spheres, triangle stripes) and places it along a parametric curve with parameters varying with noise() function as source of smooth motion.

New shapes are added layer after layer with new forms and colors.

At any time the user can pause the generation by pressing 'p', resume it with 'r' and save a 1600x1600 png with 's'.

Sources of variations are:
- primitives choice (3)
- orientation (0, 90, 180, 270 degrees)
- initial conditions
- shapes evolution
- colors evolution (only 10% will be bi-chromatic)


Press:
- 'p' to pause
- 'r' to resume
- 's' to save a 1600x1600 png image

metadata.name: CENTURY-XXX-METAFRANKE #447
metadata.description:
1 of 5 in CENTURY-XXX, Series 2
Edition of 1000

Tribute to Herbert W. Franke
“In Honor of the Dinosaur of Computer Art” 

Herbert W. Franke, a pioneer of computer art, passed away on July 16, 2022 at the age of 95. CENTURY-XXX-METAFRANKE is an homage to Franke’s MONDRIAN software developed for the Texas Instruments TI 99/4 home computer in 1979, and it’s a fundraiser to digitize his archive:

“Our goal is to raise 20,000 Euro so that ZKM Karlsruhe can digitize Herbert W. Franke’s 1,800 manuscripts and make them publicly available. If we raise more money, it will be donated to the Rütgers Foundation which supports children and young adults in Africa so that they can get access to and work with technology.” 

Each frame, a single “pixel” is added to the CENTURY-XXX-METAFRANKE image. When the software first loads, 100,000 frames are run in the background to start things off. Keep it running for hours or days to see it transform entirely — it’s an “infinite animation.”

metadata.name: PixlFlippr #495
metadata.description:
PixlFlippr is an offshoot of my "Simple Harmonic Motion" series, inspired by the complexity of life emerging through the interaction of simple 'dumb' behaviors, with intricate details emerging on multiple scales. PixlFlippr operates on a pixel level (in the form of a GLSL frag shader).

Every pixel oscillates at a single fixed frequency, slightly out-of-sync with its neighbors. There is no explicit pixel-neighborhood communication (as there would be in eg Cellular Automata), and every pixel acts autonomously, oblivious to its surroundings. Yet collectively, the entire system exhibits constantly evolving complex high level behavior on many scales, ranging from patterns & behaviors spanning a few pixels, all the way up to the level of the entire image. These are further amplified through the emergent pixel aliasing artefacts & moiré patterns. 

Also, it's trippy af. 

PS All generative mints are a seamless loop with a loop duration ranging from a few minutes to over an hour. So stick around & watch it mutate!
